                    <!-- Preparation Steps -->
                    <h2 style="font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; margin-top: 40px; color: #141312;">2. Optimization Steps</h2>
                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">01 /</span> <strong>Onion Caramelization:</strong> Finely dice your yellow onions. Heat vegetable oil in a pan and cook the onions slowly over medium heat for 12 to 15 minutes. They must turn a deep, dark brown color without burning—this deep browning serves as the flavor substrate for the entire gravy base.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">02 /</span> <strong>Spice Blooming Threshold:</strong> Drop your minced ginger, garlic, and dried spices directly into the hot onion oil. Stir rapidly for 60 seconds. Blooming the spice compounds in oil instead of water releases their full aromatic oil-soluble flavor metrics, amplifying the taste profiles.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">03 /</span> <strong>Legume Compression:</strong> Pour in your tomatoes and drained chickpeas. Cover and simmer for 20 minutes on low heat. Before serving, take a flat spatula or potato masher and firmly crush 20% of the chickpeas against the pan floor—the exposed starches will emulsify the pan liquids into a thick, restaurant-quality masala glaze.</p>
                        </div>
